  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve the limit\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\right),\n\\]\n\nlet's analyze each component step by step.\n\n### Step 1: Simplify the Cube Root Expression\n\nConsider the expression inside the cube root:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - x^3 = -x^3 + x^2 = -x^3 \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{x}\\right).\n\\]\n\nTaking the cube root of both sides:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3 \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{x}\\right)} = -x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}}.\n\\]\n\n### Step 2: Expand the Cube Root Using Binomial Approximation\n\nFor large \\( x \\), \\( \\frac{1}{x} \\) is small, so we can use the binomial expansion for \\( \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\):\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{1}{x}} \\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3x}.\n\\]\n\nSubstituting this back:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} \\approx -x \\left(1 - \\frac{1}{3x}\\right) = -x + \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\n### Step 3: Combine with the \\( +x \\) Term\n\nNow, add \\( x \\) to the approximation:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\approx \\left(-x + \\frac{1}{3}\\right) + x = \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\n### Conclusion\n\nAs \\( x \\) approaches infinity, the dominant terms cancel out, leaving us with:\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\left( \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\right) = \\frac{1}{3}.\n\\]\n\n**Answer:** The limit is 1\u20443.",
